**Q1.** (a)      (i)     State **two** vector quantities.  
  
vector quantity 1  - [[../Physics/Acceleration|Acceleration]]  
  
vector quantity 2 - Velocity  
  
(ii)     State **two** scalar quantities.  
  
scalar quantity 1 - [[../To do/Speed|Speed]]  
  
scalar quantity 2 - Distance  
  
**(2)**  
  
(b)     The helicopter shown in **Figure 1a** is moving horizontally through still air. The lift force from the helicopter’s blades is labelled **A**.  
  
![](data:image/png;base64,)  
  
(i)      Name the two [[../To do/Forces|forces]] **B** and **C** that also act on the helicopter.  
  
**B** Air resistance  
  
**C** [[../To do/Gravity|Gravity]]  
  
**(2)**  
  
(ii)     The force vectors are also shown arranged as a triangle in **Figure 1b**.  
  
State and explain how **Figure 1b** shows that the helicopter is moving at a constant velocity.  
  
As the [[../To do/Forces|forces]] across the force triangle creates a closed triangle, the velocity is constant  
  
**(2)**  
  
(c)     The lift force, **A**, is 9.5 kN and acts at an angle of 74° to the horizontal.  
  
Calculate the weight of the helicopter. Give your answer to an appropriate number of significant figures.  
  
$9.5 \times \sin (74) = Weight$  
$Weight = 9.13kN = 9130N$  
  
  
answer = 9130 N

**(Total 9 marks)**  
  
**Q2.** An ‘E-bike’ is a bicycle that is assisted by an electric motor. The figure below shows an E-bike and rider with a total [[../To do/Mass|mass]] of 83 kg moving up an incline.  
  
![](data:image/png;base64,)  
  
(a)     (i)      The cyclist begins at rest at **A** and accelerates uniformly to a speed of 6.7 m s<sup>–1</sup> at **B**.    
The distance between **A** and **B** is 50 m.    
Calculate the time taken for the cyclist to travel this distance.  
  
$s=\frac{1}{2}(u+v)t$  
$\frac{2s}{u+v}=t$  
$\frac{100}{6.7}=15s$  
  
15s  
  
**(2)**  
  
(ii)     Calculate the kinetic energy of the E-bike and rider when at **B**. Give your answer to an appropriate number of significant figures.  
  
$\frac{1}{2}mv^2$  
$\frac{1}{2}\times 83 \times 6.7^2 = 1863$  
  
1860J  
  
**(2)**  
  
(iii)    Calculate the [[../Physics/Gravitational potential|gravitational potential energy]] gained by the E-bike and rider between **A** and **B**.  
  
$83 \times 9.81 \times 3 = 2440$  
  
2440J  
  
**(2)**  
  
(b)     Between **A** and **B**, the [[../Physics/Work done|work done]] by the electric motor is 3700 J, and the [[../Physics/Work done|work done]] by the cyclist pedalling is 5300 J.  
  
(i)      Calculate the wasted energy as the cyclist travels from **A** to **B**.  
  
$3700 + 5300 = 9000J$  
$2440 + 1860 = 4300$  
$9000 - 4300 = 4700$  
  
4700J  
  
**(2)**  
  
(ii)     State **two** causes of this wasted energy.  
  
Cause 1 - Friction between wheels and the slope  
Cause 2 - Friction between the chain and gears  
  
**(2)**  
  
**(Total 10 marks)**  
  
**Q3.** In the 17<sup>th</sup> century, when thinking about [[../To do/Forces|forces]], Galileo imagined a ball moving in the absence of air resistance on a frictionless track as shown in **Figure 1**.  
  
**Figure 1**  
  
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**  
  
(a)     Galileo thought that, under these circumstances, the ball would reach position **C** if released from rest at position **A**. Position **C** is the same height above the ground as **A**.  
  
Using ideas about energy, explain why Galileo was correct.  
  
In the absence of air resistance and friction, there would be no energy dissapated, so all of the initial GPE will be converted to $K_E$ and then all of that $K_E$ would be converted into the same amount of GPE as at the start, reaching the same height of C  
  
**(3)**  
  
(b)     Galileo then imagined that the track was changed, as shown in **Figure 2**.  
  
**Figure 2**  
  
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**  
  
The slope beyond **B** was now horizontal.  
  
On the axes below, sketch a speed – time graph for the ball from its release at **A** until it reaches the position **X** shown in **Figure 2**. Indicate on your graph the time when the ball is at **B**.  
  
![[../Extra Files/Pasted image 20250126133258.png|Pasted image 20250126133258.png]]  
  
**(3)**  
  
(c)     Newton later published his three laws of motion.  
  
Explain how Newton’s first law of motion is illustrated by the motion of the ball between **B** and **X**.

**Q4. Figure 1** shows car **A** being towed at a steady speed up a slope which is inclined at 5.0° to the horizontal. Assume that the resistive [[../To do/Forces|forces]] acting on car **A** are negligible.  
  
**Figure 1**  
  
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**  
  
**Figure 2** represents a simplified version of the [[../To do/Forces|forces]] acting on car **A** at the instant shown in **Figure 1**.  
  
**Figure 2**  
  
**![](data:image/png;base64,)**  
  
(a)     (i)      Car **A** has a mass of 970 kg. Show that the component of its weight that acts parallel to the slope is approximately 830 N.  
$970 \times 9.81 = 9515.7 N$  
$Component \space of \space weight \space down \space slope = 9515.7\sin(5) = 829.34N \approx 830N$  
  
**(2)**  
  
(ii)     Calculate the energy stored in the tow rope as car **A** is towed up the slope at a steady speed. The tow rope obeys Hooke’s law and has a stiffness of 2.5 × 10<sup>4</sup> Nm<sup>–1</sup>.  
  
  
  
energy stored \_**\_**\_**\_**\_**\_**\__ J  
  
**(4)**  
  
(b)     The tow rope is attached to a fixing point on car **A** using a metal hook. During the ascent of the slope the fixing point snaps and the metal hook becomes detached from car **A**. The metal hook gains speed due to the energy stored in the rope. State and explain how the speed gained by the hook would have changed if the rope used had a stiffness greater than 2.5 × 10<sup>4</sup> Nm<sup>–1</sup>.  
  
If the rope was stiffer, the speed gained by the hook would decrease as there would be less $E_P$ to convert into $E_K$ so the speed gained would be less  
  
**(3)**  
  
**(Total 9 marks)**
